Sentence_Uncivil: numbers cannot be mapped to a double datatype using match_mapping_type.  That part probably needs clarification though I'm not sure how to do it. Basically, the json parser assumes the wider datatype that is not a BigDecimal/BigInteger. So floating-point numbers will be detected as a `double` rather than a `float` and integers will be detected as a `long` rather than an `integer`. You can dynamically map floating-point numbers to doubles by using `double` as a `match_mapping_type` and `double` as a type i
Sentence_Civil: Numbers cannot be mapped to a double datatype using match_mapping_type. I'm still uncertain how to handle this part. The json parser assumes the wider data type other than BigDecimal/BigInteger, so floating-point numbers will be detected as 'double' rather than as an _float, and integers will become progressively longer than an_integer. We can dynamically map floating point numbers to doubles by using -double as the corresponding s.

Sentence_Civil: Mail classes are likely to be loaded at server level, resulting in only one default mapping. Sentence_Civil: I further investigated this issue, and I came to realize that accessing files via the Unix file system (File class) is no longer possible. Sentence_Uncivil: I am having the same issue.  On Windows 10, there is a feature called UI Scaling described in this article: http  This is a good feature for people with vision problems to make the text and GUI elements bigger in most Windows programs.  However, when this feature is enabled, two very bad things happen for libGDX:  1. In full screen mode, we only see the upper left portion of the viewport zoomed in according to the degree of the UI scaling.  2. Nearest Neighbor pixel rendering screws up and shows blurry pi
Sentence_Civil: I'm facing the same issue. On Windows 10, there's a feature called UI Scaling, as described in this article: http This feature is intended for people with vision problems to make the text and GUI elements larger in most Windows programs. However, when this feature' is enabled, two significant issues arise for libGDX: 1. In full-screen mode, we only see the upper left portion of the viewport zoomed in according to the degree of UA scaling. 2. Nearest Neighbor pixel rendering causes issues and results in blurry pi.

Sentence_Uncivil: Most graphics subsystems max out around 30k pixels in either direction, so any time you're close to that, you're likely to run into trouble. Are you actually below 30k pixels in either dimension?   In other circumstances (i.e. a hidpi display, or sizing up), the limit can be even worse—around 15k pixels.  This is a funky OS limitation that we obviously can't control, but if we can figure out where it's failing, perhaps we can put in an error message or warning about it.
Sentence_Civil: In most graphics subsystems, the limit is typically around 30k pixels in either direction, so if you're near that limit, you may encounter issues. Are you actually below 30K pixels on either dimension? In other circumstances (e.g., a hiddenpi display, or sizing up), the limitation can be even higher, around 15k Pixels. This is essentially an OS limitation that we cannot control, but based on the location where it's failing, we can include an error message or warning message.

Sentence_Uncivil: Strong upvote here. For things like FlatBuffers (or I think even protobuf) that generate one file per table/struct, this is a big issue. Sentence_Civil: Strong upvote here. For platforms like FlatBuffers (or I believe even protobuf), where the output is a directory using ctx.actions.declare_directory, this can be quite challenging. The best options I can think of are to either write  sysfs custom rules and declare the file as if it were destined for 'a' directory, write an linter rule that enforces the use of one struct per file with corresponding matching name (which many developers dislike when there are several small dependent strus that aren't meant to be used separately), or write your own custom build script.

Sentence_Civil: Okay, I finally got it right. My MacBook Pro didn't perform as expected; I simply had a virus scanner running on it. Sentence_Civil: The scam mentioned above has been around for over ten years, and I've been repeatedly called upon in Australia by individuals with an Indian accent. Unfortunately, we cannot fully protect computer users from their own ignorance. If someone thinks their ISP or Microsoft will contact them randomly, they may have a low intelligence level. The best defence, other than hanging up, is to provide  sarcasm and request if they can be reached. For the verified bank account, I used merely requesting e-mail addresses and offering to call them back.

Sentence_Civil: I find it odd that graylog rename fields are still required for backward compatibility, even though they are no longer required. Sentence_Uncivil: I kinda doubt the libGDX devs will want to break compatibility for every single existing game for this. Unit tests, like the ones libGDX uses to test PRs, sometimes need to run on headless machines and don't have this as a valid option anyway. Invisible and silent unit tests also have a limited range of behavior they can actually detect; games often need a human being to point out that, say, too many zangulorgs are spawning in an area, or in a visually-obvious pattern, and not enough blanyayools spawn in
Sentence_Civil: I have reservations about breaking compatibility for every existing game, especially when testing unit tests like libGDX's PRs. Sometimes, even on headless machines, invisible and silent unit testing may not provide the desired functionality. It'll be necessary to identify areas where too many zangulorgs are spawning, or a visually-obvious pattern, and ensure that not enough blanyayols morph into an area.

Sentence_Uncivil: e them. A `LinkedList` in Java is horrible! A two element `LinkedList` uses up exactly the same memory as a 10 element `ArrayList`. Sentence_Civil: I strongly disagree with the usage of LinkedList in Java. It's not ideal that a two-element Linked List uses up the same memory as ten-element ArrayList. One of the reasons why the current headers consume so much memory is the need for an "ObjectToObjectmap".

Sentence_Civil: If we generate a new texture atlas with libGDX Texture Atlas without the defined format or other key properties, it might not work as expected. In my opinion, having everything optional doesn't make it optimum file especification; it makes life harder for third-par developers who may need to maintain compatibilité.

Sentence_Civil: I recall why I was asked to open this issue back then. However, upon further reflection, I don't believe logging at the tail end (ie the video-provider component) is the appropriate approach. If we want to identify the reason for a closed loop, we should log the root action (e.g., lock cameras, enter breakout room) and use log correlation to link it to the end. Regarding errors, screen sharing should have clearly defined logs and erro messages.

Sentence_Uncivil: @user First, thanks for trying to get K-9 Mail to work with PGP/MIME encrypted/signed messages!  However, I don't think this is the right approach. This pull request doesn't address the core problem that prevents us from having proper PGP/MIME support. It's the fact that K-9 Mail doesn't store messages in a way that allows reconstructing byte-identical copies of the original message. Worse, we can't even retrieve the structure of the original MIME tree. This pull request contains a lot of very nasty hacks
Sentence_Civil: @user First, thank you for your efforts in getting K-9 Mail to work with PGP/MIME encrypted/signed messages! However, I don't believe this approach is the right one. The core problem that prevents us from achieving proper PPG/ MIME support is that K9 Mail doesn''s storage methods do not allow for reconstructing byte-identical copies of the original message. Furthermore, we can' t retrieve the structure of its original MME tree. This pull request contains several hacks that are quite unpleasant solutions.

Sentence_Uncivil: ``` I strongly recommend to mention Acoustic Echo Cancellation in the wiki or the docs. Reason: Echo AVOIDING is always better than Echo Cancellation. No matter how good the algorithm in Flash might be it cannot beat a session, where there is no acoustic echo in the first place. Like when everybody is on headsets. The often used practice "everybody not talking mutes his mic" is helpful but can generate some nasty audio artifacts when a mic is unmuted. I am more than happy to explain why, but think most pe
Sentence_Civil: I strongly recommend mentioning Acoustic Echo Cancellation in the wiki or the documentation. Reason: Echo AVOIDING is always better than EchoCancellations. No matter how good the algorithm in Flash might be, it cannot overcome a session where there is no incoming coustic echo. For example, when everyone is wearing headsets, the often used practice of "everybody not talking mutes his mic" can be helpful, but it can lead to unwanted audio artifacts when muted. I'm happy to explain why, although I don't think most people would appreciate the explanation.

Sentence_Uncivil: @user I don't think using `final String topic = topicName;` is a good idea. "_" appear as result of replacement of ":" and "/" in the full topic name (URI as in "persistent://tenant/ns/topic") that snowflake connector does internally to generate table name compatible with the snowflake. Theoretically, topic2table mapping of `"persistent___tenant_ns_topic:cooltablename"` might work though it di
Sentence_Civil: @user I don't believe using final String topic = topicName; is the best approach. If I recall correctly, sink can use multiple input topics (via '--inputs') and we should route them to appropriate destinations. The term "_" appears as a result of replacing ":" with "/" in the full topic name (URI as in "persistent://tenant/ns/topic"), which is handled internally by the snowflake connector to generate corresponding table names compatible with the Snowfl. In theory, utilizing, an alternative approach of topic2table mapping of p2Tablename' might be viable, although it may not be ideal.

Sentence_Civil: As mentioned previously, different factors can contribute to the lower response on TechEmpowered. Hardware: Your CPU core is newer and has a higher base speed, enabling it to push more instructions per core. The 40 ( 40 + 40 HT ) Core server they use is primarily based on FB-DIMM, which introduces latency in inner communication. Moreover, servers tend to use FS-DMM, an entirely different beast from your Unbuffered-Diamonds. Perhaps your CPU is using SSL, or maybe yours is already.

Sentence_Civil: The long incubation period is a significant factor in Elasticsearch's success. We recently decided to baseline Elastisearch 8.0 on Java 17 shortly after it went GA, and we currently have an open PR (https://github.com/elastic/exastaticsearch/pull/90571) to upgrade the bundled runtime to Java 19 as well. There'd be no fundamental reluctance to adopt new language and run time features. The difference lies in how historically we have had to wait, rather than waiting for years.

Sentence_Uncivil: > HTTP tunnel is an obvious and horrible security hole. Taking into consideration that MySQL user passwords are often not very secured, never change, etc.  You always can hide your script by using random chars in path and nobody except you will not know path. And you still need to know DB login and pass. Also .htaccess with IP grants still actual. Not a problem. Also nobody will use this way if normal SSH access present. But sometimes you have no way and must use it
Sentence_Civil: The security hole in HTTP tunnel is obvious and significant. Considering that MySQL user passwords are often not highly secured, it's important to consider that they may not always change. For example, you can hide your script by using random characters in the path. However, nobody except you will be aware of the hidden path; otherwise, the script will not be used. Additionally,.htaccess with IP grants is still valid. This issue shouldn't be an issue. Furthermore, there'll be no need to use this approach if normal SSH access is present. Sometimes, we must use it because we don''T have no other options and need it.

Sentence_Civil: When considering schema+data version, it's possible that multiple changes can be made in each version. If done correctly, each change would be separate and tolerant of failure. However, they may not be idempotent, so if you use 2.9.0-migration1 but encounter an error on 3.9.0migration2, you won't retry 1.9.0-0migrate1. For that reason, all the migration tools I've used and written treat migrations as a list of changes.

Sentence_Civil: The default set supplied in JAF and the ones configured via Spring are options two and less comprehensive. Sentence_Civil: Not only empty queries, but a query containing only whitespace will fail too. It's quite frustrating from logical perspective -- empty strings are not very special. "400 Bad Request" is not an appropriate response.

Sentence_Civil: I can reproduce this issue on version 4.17.0. When accessing the conversation list after a fresh unlock using the new "screen unlock" feature within the Signal app, pressing the back button returns the user to the pattern unlock screen. However, it doesn't re-lock Signal. If you press back again, or press home and subsequently regain Signal, the patterns unlock screens are not present, and you are taken to your conversation lists as expected. It's important to proactively enlist your screen unlock pattern when the errant unlock button is present.

Sentence_Uncivil: I think I found the **root cause**: the **libtool crap in freeswitch** (again). configure finds libopusenc and declares the related defs. however, when mod_opusfile.c gets compiled, they are simply not used. And therefore the [write file part](https://github.com/signalwire/freeswitch/blob/master/src/mod/formats/mod_opusfile/mod_opusfile.c#L222) of it gets skipped and a generic error returned, without giving any log message about the reason =8-( . It finally gets linked against libopusenc, but that's obvio
Sentence_Civil: I believe I've identified the root cause of the issue: the libtool component in freeswitch. When configure finds Libopusenc and declares the related definitions, it is not used. As a result, the [write file part](https://github.com/signalwire/freeswitch/master/src/mod_opufile/mode_ofpusfile.c#L222) gets skipped and logged without providing  definite log message. It eventually gets linked against lopulsen, but that's not necessary.

Sentence_Uncivil: > it sucks that we need to implement grow-ability to save cost of zeroing out where we already have allocated all the memory or is there any other advantage?.  The problem is the memory is not initialized when we allocated it, so it has garbage in it, and therefore we need to initialize the parts we're going to use. And initialization can take a while if your buffer size is big (like a gigabyte, as some people do).  > Instead, if we reserved numBucket bytes at the start of buffer and used those for markin
Sentence_Civil: It's not ideal that we need to implement grow-ability to avoid zeroing out where we already allocated all the memory. Is there any way we can improve this situation? The problem is that the RAM is not initialized when we allocated it, so it contains garbage. We need first to initialize the parts we're going to use, which can take a while if the buffer size is large (like tens of GB), then we could use those reserved numBucket bytes at the start of the Buffer and used those for markin.

Looks like when this issue occurred ,  countdownLatch.await() line was missing from the code so hazelcast lock acquiring method was made synchronized.  After that when we found out that await is misssing we added await. Now it works without making the method synchronized. Thanks for your help. Apologies , Looks like a
Sentence_Civil: @user We recently re-analyzed our code. We were calling Couchbase asynchronously using RxJava, so we had added 'countdown latch' in the Spring Controller method to make the client wait for the response. It seems that when this issue occurred, the countdownLatch.await() line was missing from the code, resulting in synchronization of the hazelcast lock acquiring method. However, after discovering that await is not missing, we added "awaited." The method now works without requiring coordinating the method itself. Thank you for your assistance.

Sentence_Civil: *Original comment by @user I spent some time considering this and I'm still concerned that the solution we came up with is too complex. Sentence_Civil: The system has reached an extreme point where Elasticsearch is complaining about its inability to write logs, which are sent via rsyslog to our Logstashes. Elexsearch has already written millions of data/writes into audit-logs and are now scraped by filebeat. It is becoming increasingly challenging for Filebeat to keep up with scraping all the necessary log files from that audit.json. We need to be able to filter events before they are written to the logfile. Additionally, I've observed high CPU usage by Filebeaten, even with its limited resources.

Sentence_Uncivil: ToS are not law - it just means that if you violate them, youtube is free to withhold their services to you (i.e. terminate your account & block your IP if they're extra mean) - it only becomes illegal if you agree to the ToS by using their services through their official clients (i.e. the website, the regular app, etc.)  Cease and Desist letters don't have to have any reason to exist; just the threat of a legal battle which Google would 100% lose would stop any development being done on Newpipe, since no
Sentence_Civil: ToS are not laws; rather, they serve as a guideline for how YouTube can handle violations, including terminating your account and blocking your IP if they perceive it as being unreasonable. It becomes illegal unless you agree to the Tos by using their official clients, such as the website or regular app. Cease and Desist letters do not need monetary grounds to exist; the threat of bringing Google into infringement would prevent any development on Newpipe.

Sentence_Uncivil: `--define` is more than just `goog.define`s. You can also have non-Closure `@define`s (like `COMPILED` in base.js). Sentence_Civil: The term "--define" can be interpreted in various ways, including non-Closure "@defs" in base.js. A bundle cannot replace these values, and it doesn't make sense for them to go in "CLOSURE_[UNCOMPILED_]DEFINES." It would be confusing if the compiler always outputs the Closure defines as a result. Sentence_Uncivil: @user You need to add `.toWebElement()`:  ```java actions().moveToElement($(".gsfi").toWebElement()).perform(); ```  The point is that `$(".gsfi")` is not a "real" `WebElement`, but a proxy object (created by Selenide). If you call "usual" methods on this proxy objects, everything works.  But actions builder doesn't call "usual" methods, but uses black magic (which fails with the proxy object).  Namely, actions builder calls `BeanToJsonConverter` which uses reflection and iterates all _properties_ of give
Sentence_Civil: @user To add the required code to the WebElement() function, you should use the following code block: java actions().moveToElem($(".gsfi").toWebEllement(perform()); - The point is that '$$" is not a "real" Web Element but merely  s proxy object created by Selenide. When calling "usual" methods on this proxy objects, everything works fine. However, the actions builder doesn't call "normal" techniques but instead resorts to black magic (which fails with the proxy). In short, actionsBuilder calls java actionBuildER, which utilizes reflection and iterates all the properties of give.

Sentence_Civil: ### Resource Management A conversation with @user revealed one of the key goals of The Sequence abstraction: the ability to manage resources. It has been so successful that Druid has never encountered a query-related resource leak. Impressive! As @utilisateur observed, an operator is essentially merely closable iterator with some additional goodies. Closeable Iterators can lead to resource loss. Sentence_Uncivil: @user I think we might already be at peak-workaround. The webrtc folks, in their infinite wisdom, do not seem to think it's important to support "ringing." As soon as I build a PeerConnection, it tries to take over and play an AudioTrack w/ STREAM_VOICE_CALL whether the AudioTrack is enabled or not.  If I try to play sounds with MODE_RINGTONE, they'll just get hijacked by webrtc and end up in the earpiece.  The only thing I can do is play the ringtone into the voice call stream, but turn the speaker on.
Sentence_Civil: @user I believe we might be at the peak-workaround. The webrtc folks, in their infinite wisdom, don't seem to believe it's important to support "ringing." As soon as I build a PeerConnection, it automatically takes over and plays an AudioTrack with STREAM_VOICE_CALL, regardless of whether the AudioTracker is enabled or not. If I try to play sounds with MODE_RINGTONE, they will be hijacked by webrentc and end up in the earpiece. Only thing I can do is play the Ringtone into the voice call stream, but turn the speaker on.

Sentence_Uncivil: The server considers someone incapable of receiving messages if their GCM or APN id is reported as being invalid/unregistered by the GCM or APN servers.  This typically happens when they uninstall the app, in which case you do want Signal to revert back to SMS.  However, it could inadvertently happen if they use titanium backup, some weird rom, a 3rd party client, etc.  I'd be interested to know if this contact somehow fucks with their phone, or if they're a total normal/stock user who someone got unregis
Sentence_Civil: If the GCM or APN servers report an invalid or unregistered id, it can lead to the loss of SMS functionality. It's worth identifying the root cause and finding a solution to this issue.

Sentence_Uncivil: This is what causes problem with date values:  ``` Unrecognized type 'java.sql.Date' - can't convert to numeric ```  DBeaver thinks that this column has numeric data type. This is because you second column has the same alias as the real table column (date_key). DBeaver tries to discover real attribute data type from database metadata whenever it is possible. Smarty pants.  Workaround - set some alias for your expression. And I'll think how to handle this problem better..
Sentence_Civil: This is what causes the issue with date values:  Unrecognized type 'java.sql.Date' can't convert to numeric. DBeaver believes this column has numerical data type because the second column shares the same alias as the real table column (date_key). Whenever possible, BDeAver seeks real attribute datatype from database metadata. Workaround: Set an arbitrary naming convention for your expression. I'll consider how to handle this problem better.

Sentence_Uncivil: The test ran close to midnight. In SQL, when casting `TIME` to any other temporal type, the current date is added. The engine gets the current date at some point in time, and the test creates the expected value at some other time. When these two happen at a different day, the test fails...  To fix we need to assert that the actual value is this or the next day, an ugly generalization...
Sentence_Civil: The test ran close to midnight. In SQL, when casting TIME to any other temporal type, the current date is added. The engine receives the actual date at some point in time, and the test creates its expected value at a different time. When these two events occur on distinctly different days, they cause the testing to fail. To address this, we need to assert that the real value is either this day or the next day, resulting in an unattractive generalization.

Sentence_Civil: @user Since the decider is part of the balancing process, the allocator will attempt to find the "best" weights that still satisfy all decideurs, attempting to balance the chips evenly but still permitting uneven allocation in the event of a disk limit issue. Sentence_Uncivil: Elastisearch comes *"broken by default"*. In order to have it listen on a network socket, you have to add **two** entries to your `elastisearch.yml` file:  **C:\ProgramData\Elastic\Elasticsearch\config\elasticsearch.yml**:      network.host: 0.0.0.0     discovery.seed_hosts: []  The first option will have Elastisearch open an actual network listening socket.   The second option is needed to satisfy *something*. Nobody cares what the option is; it's just needed to make it shut up and do its job.
Sentence_Civil: Elastisearch comes with a default broken state. To enable it to listen on  sysfs or any other network socket, you need to add two entries to your elastisearch.yml file. C:ProgramDataElasticElasticsearchconfigelatsearch_ymml**: network.host: 0.0.0.0 discovery.seed_hosts: [] The first option will enable ElasticSearch to open encapsulated network listening socket. The second option is necessary to satisfy satisfactory. Nobody cares about the choice; it's just needed to keep the system running smoothly.

Sentence_Uncivil: `Future.sync()` can raise any type of throwable.  To be strict, its method signature should have `throws Exception`. Sentence_Civil: The current implementation of Future.sync() can handle any type of throwable. To be precise, its method signature should include the phrase "throws Exception." However, we chose not to include it for the sake of improved code clarity. While we find it unattractive, it is not as bad as having to handle every f.Synch() call individually, even if you don't have a strong desire to do so.

Sentence_Civil: Warning: This implementation requires leaving the cluster and undergoing lengthy checks and subsequent optional fixes. The method implemented by kimchy involves taking the defect node down (shutdown api or kill), allowing the ES cluster to adjust to the new situation, enabling a "fix" check setting value explicitly in the defects nodes index setting, and starting the noDE once again. After completing the check and repair phase, the Node will enter re-enabled index structures and attempt to rejoin the group.

Sentence_Uncivil: Model snapshots and the `latest_record_time_stamp` field are emitted by the autodetect process, internally autodetect works at a second resolution and when it writes a model snapshot as JSON to be consumed by Elasticsearch it converts the seconds to milliseconds.   http  I'm labelling this as `won't fix` because converting autodetect to sub-second resolution is a large undertaking.
Sentence_Civil: Model snapshots and the latest_record_time_stamp field are emitted by the autodetect process. Internally, autodestecting works at a second resolution, and when it writes sysfs to be consumed by Elasticsearch, it converts the seconds to milliseconds. I'm labeling this as 'won't fix' because converting autodétec to sub-second resolution is incredibly complex.

Sentence_Uncivil: was working fine in modes and tools as their number is small but in libraries it was breaking as the no of libraries is around 130. Sentence_Civil: The current implementation was working fine in modes and tools as their number is small, but when it came to libraries, it was causing issues as the number of libraries is around 130. What I did: I modified the contributionAdded function to avoid using threading, making the addition tothe list slow and introducing an annoying time lag. So, I rewritten the code to ensure that the list is only updated once all the contributions are added.

Sentence_Uncivil: Even if you deploy BTM in separate JVMs, you must give each instance a different server IDs as that parameter is used to globally discriminate transaction manager instances.  This is described here (http://docs.codehaus.org/display/BTM/Configuration2x#Configuration2x-Transactionenginesettings) although much too succinctly.  If you ever configure two TM instances with an identical server ID you may end up with one TM instance's recoverer rolling back in-progress transactions of another running instance, an
Sentence_Civil: Even if you deploy BTM in separate JVMs, it's important to provide each instance with a different server ID to differentiate transaction manager instances. This is described in detail here (http://docs.codehaus.org/display/BTM/Configuration2x#Configuration2X-Transactionenginesettings), but it could be improved by providing more concise information. For example, combining two TM instances with an identical serverID could result in both instances' recoverers rolling back in-progress transactions of another running instance, which could lead to unexpected behavior. It'd be beneficial to have separating the server identity between the two separate patches.

Sentence_Civil: I have been consistently satisfied with the accuracy and performance of indexed point-data. While performance can be improved, it is still outstanding in my opinion. The only downside is LUCENE-4978, but there are workarounds for achieving accuracy: either index a micro-circle/box instead of one point, or slightly buffer the query shape. However, when indexing non-point data, there is balancing accuracy & precision in ES on issue #2361 with Lucene 4.7's new [Ser] feature. I plan to address this in the es on Issue #2461 in ESR on topic in LOCE on the new[Se] features.

Sentence_Civil: @user There's nothing wrong about your English level as far as I can tell. Sentence_Uncivil: The load order is pretty much undefined, so I wouldn't rely on it.  Whether or not the map plugin breaks depends on the binary compatibility of the different versions, that's tricky to say.  What I've done in the past to work around issues like these was to include the library's code as a git submodule (from a fork) and then update the library to use a specific version. That's messy and requires tracking changes, but is often the only sane way to deal with jar hell.
Sentence_Civil: The load order is currently undefined, so we shouldn't rely on it. The compatibility of the map plugin with different versions can be tricky to determine. In the past, we have worked around issues like this by including the library's code as a git submodule (from  sandbox) and updating the libraries to use whichever specific version. It'd be messy and require tracking changes, but it' surprisingly the only viable approach when dealing with jar issues.
